<br>
At night on Kerra Isle, the silence is a warm blanket. The creatures here move without sound when they want to, which they rarely do. When they do make noise it’s playful growls, and the sound of kittens wrestling in the sand. <br>
<br>
But their fur makes for good hunting. Their friends, the tigers and gorillas, make for good poaching. And the Kerrans are so far removed from the world at large, when foreigners come to their lands, it goes largely unnoticed. <br>
<br>
(I was there one night, a ranger with foolishly little use for violence thinks. I was there and saw my own people slaughtering these poor creatures, and I could do nothing to stop them.) <br>
<br>
But they come often, the foreigners. Roary has survived enough attacks to know that. He knows the poor Catfisher has a price on his tail. He knows the rest of the world sees his people as simpletons at best, savages at worst. <br>
<br>
Tonight he can here them making their way across the water. He can smell the leather of their armor and the stink of their battlefear. <br>
<br>
The silence at night is like a blanket, but the cries of the dying in the daylight is like the cacophony of Hell. <br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
The half-elven bandit felt the blood of his victim spurt over his hand, his dagger plunged into the man’s back. He went quickly through the man’s pockets and looked back at his fellows. <br>
<br>
&quot;Anything worthwhile?&quot; asked a charlatan, an aging and hungry-looking halfling. <br>
<br>
The half-elf threw something to her. A Recondite ring. <br>
<br>
&quot;One of ours,&quot; she whispered. <br>
<br>
&quot;Irik’s. He’s the one who killed Irik,&quot; the half-elf muttered, sitting down at the water’s edge. &quot;Have you ever seen daylight, charlatan?&quot;<br>
<br>
She looked at him curiously. <br>
<br>
&quot;Daylight. Have you ever left this place? Have you ever seen the sun?&quot;<br>
<br>
She shook her head. <br>
<br>
&quot;I’ve been here my whole life.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;So have I.&quot; <br>
<br>
A gruff voice yelled out from the darkness. More warriors from Shadow Haven. More trouble. <br>
<br>
&quot;I’d like to see the sun someday,&quot; the half-elf said. He went to wipe the blood from his hands, but realized it would always be there. There would always be blood on his hands. <br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
The thoughts of a wisp are hard to understand. They’re not really here, you know. Not the way you or I are. <br>
<br>
That happy place people go between lives? That light at the end of the tunnel? <br>
<br>
We’ll all be will o’ the wisps someday, friends. If only for a little while. <br>
<br>
The longer you stay a wisp, they say, the more fulfilling your next life will be. Those who pass quickly between lives often meet with tragedy or boredom, and some folks believe there’s no difference in between the two. <br>
<br>
No, they’re not undead, lad. They’re just passing through. Somewhere, in a place no mortals can go, there are more lightstones than anyone can imagine. And one by one these lightstones begin to glow as a soul – maybe an elf’s, maybe a rat’s – picks up its temporary home. And off they go, to bring light to the darkest nights. If only for a little while. <br>
<br>
How unfortunate, really, that someone has put a price on soulcatchers these days… <br>
